<paragraph blockId="34.[151,897,1854,1915]" box="[151,897,1889,1915]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Rivero’s white-lipped frog, Sapo-rana rugoso de Rivero, Jujüku</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,152,498]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
rio-Amorós 1998a). It also occurs in the northern Brazilian and Colombian Amazon (
<bibRefCitation author="Heyer, W. R. &amp; Pyburn, W. F." box="[1148,1431,152,178]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="560 - 566" refId="ref35246" refString="Heyer, W. R. &amp; Pyburn, W. F. (1983) Leptodactylus riveroi, a new frog species from Amazonia, South America (Anura: Leptodactylidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 96, 560 - 566." type="journal article" year="1983">Heyer and Pyburn 1983</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lynch, J. D. &amp; Vargas Ramirez M. A." box="[151,537,192,218]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="579 - 589" refId="ref36238" refString="Lynch, J. D. &amp; Vargas Ramirez M. A. (2001) Lista preliminar de especies de anuros del Departamento del Guania, Colombia. Revista de la Academia Colombiana de Ciencias Exactas, Fisicas y Naturales, 24, 579 - 589." type="journal article" year="2001">
Lynch and 
<collectingRegion box="[281,360,192,218]" country="Venezuela" name="Vargas" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Vargas</collectingRegion>
Ramírez 2001
</bibRefCitation>
). Our specimen has a SVL of 
<quantity box="[889,971,192,218]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="54.0">54 mm</quantity>
and it conforms to the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Heyer, W. R. &amp; Pyburn, W. F." box="[211,496,232,258]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="560 - 566" refId="ref35246" refString="Heyer, W. R. &amp; Pyburn, W. F. (1983) Leptodactylus riveroi, a new frog species from Amazonia, South America (Anura: Leptodactylidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 96, 560 - 566." type="journal article" year="1983">Heyer and Pyburn 1983</bibRefCitation>
). The dorsolateral folds are bordered laterally by an indistinct darker gray stripe. The flanks are gray with symmetrical supra axillary black spots. A dark gray canthal stripe begins on the tip of the snout but does not reach the eye. A black supratympanic fold extends from the eye to the rear of the tympanum. A distinct white stripe extends posteriorly to the scapular region from a point below the eye. The venter is white with small brown dots on the throat, and larger spots on the chest and belly (unlike the striking reticulated pattern seen in 
<bibRefCitation author="Rivero, J. A." box="[461,612,432,458]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="155 - 158" refId="ref37084" refString="Rivero, J. A. (1968) A new species of Elosia (Amphibia: Salientia) from Mt. Duida, Venezuela. American Museum Novitates, 2334, 155 - 158." type="journal article" year="1968">Rivero 1968</bibRefCitation>
). Our specimen was sitting 0.5 m from the edge of Canaracuni stream at night. Medium-sized 
<emphasis box="[431,582,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Leptodatylus</emphasis>
are known as jujüku by the local inhabitants.
</paragraph>
